n (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda de Cumbe was born in 1351, in Smeeth, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She married William de Cumbe in 1375, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1425, in Brabourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1351–1425":"1351–1425","1333–1395":"1333–1395","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1370–1425":"1370–1425","1425":"1425","1333":"1333","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1351":"1351","1395":"1395","1370":"1370","Cumbe Manor, Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotts Hall, Smeeth, Kent, England":"Smeeth, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradbourne, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotts Hall, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, 